# === Catonsville 9 / Plowshares 8 — Berrigan brothers (both cases) ===

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Daniel Berrigan","first_name":"Daniel","last_name":"Berrigan","description":"Daniel Berrigan was a Jesuit priest, poet, and one of the most prominent peace activists in U.S. history. On May 17, 1968 he and eight others — the Catonsville 9 — entered the draft board office in Catonsville, Maryland, removed 378 draft files, and burned them in the parking lot with homemade napalm in protest of the Vietnam War. He was convicted in October 1968 and sentenced on November 8 to three years in federal prison. He went underground rather than report to prison, was the first priest ever placed on the FBI Most Wanted list, and was arrested at Block Island, Rhode Island in August 1970; he served 18 months at the federal prison camp at Danbury, Connecticut.\n\nOn September 9, 1980, with his brother Philip Berrigan and six others — the Plowshares 8 — he entered the General Electric Re-Entry Division in King of Prussia, Pennsylvania, damaged nose cones for the Mark 12A nuclear warhead with household hammers, and poured blood on weapons documents. He was convicted in February 1981 and sentenced to 3-10 years in Pennsylvania state prison; the conviction was reduced to time served on appeal in April 1990. He died on April 30, 2016, age 94.","state":"Maryland","race":"White","gender":"Male","birthdate":"1921-05-09","death_date":"2016-04-30","ideologies":["Anti-war","Catholic","Plowshares","Pacifism"],"affiliation":["Society of Jesus","Catonsville 9","Plowshares 8","Catholic Worker"],"era":"1960s","in_custody":false,"released":true,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Federal Correctional Institution Danbury","institution_city":"Danbury","institution_state":"Connecticut","charges":"Federal destruction of government property — May 17, 1968 Catonsville draft-board burning of 378 draft files with homemade napalm","arrest_date":"1968-05-17","incarceration_date":"1970-08-11","release_date":"1972-02-24","sentence":"3 years federal prison; served 18 months at FCI Danbury after underground period","convicted":"Yes — federal jury verdict, U.S. District Court for the District of Maryland, October 10, 1968"},{"institution_name":"Pennsylvania Department of Corrections","institution_state":"Pennsylvania","charges":"Pennsylvania state burglary, conspiracy, criminal mischief — September 9, 1980 Plowshares 8 hammering of Mark 12A nuclear warhead nose cones at the GE Re-Entry Division in King of Prussia","arrest_date":"1980-09-09","incarceration_date":"1980-09-09","sentence":"3-10 years state prison; reduced to time served on appeal April 1990","convicted":"Yes — Pennsylvania state conviction, February 1981"}]}' || true

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Philip Berrigan","first_name":"Philip","last_name":"Berrigan","description":"Philip Berrigan was a former Josephite priest, decorated U.S. Army Second World War combat veteran, and one of the central organizers of the Catholic Left peace movement of the 1960s through 2000s. With his brother Daniel he led the May 17, 1968 Catonsville 9 raid on the Catonsville, Maryland draft board, in which 378 draft files were taken and burned with homemade napalm. Already under federal sentence for the October 1967 Baltimore Custom House blood pouring (the Baltimore 4), he received the longest Catonsville 9 sentence — 3.5 years — reflecting his prior conviction. He was arrested in 1970 after going underground and served years at the federal prison at Lewisburg, Pennsylvania.\n\nOn September 9, 1980 he was one of the eight Plowshares 8 activists who hammered Mark 12A nose cones at the GE Re-Entry Division in King of Prussia, Pennsylvania. He was a co-founder of Jonah House and the Plowshares Movement and continued symbolic disarmament actions until shortly before his death. He was married to fellow peace activist Elizabeth McAlister (also in this database). He died on December 6, 2002, age 79.","state":"Maryland","race":"White","gender":"Male","birthdate":"1923-10-05","death_date":"2002-12-06","ideologies":["Anti-war","Catholic","Plowshares","Pacifism","Anti-nuclear"],"affiliation":["Society of St. Joseph (Josephites)","Catonsville 9","Plowshares 8","Jonah House","U.S. Army (WWII)"],"era":"1960s","in_custody":false,"released":true,"cases":[{"institution_name":"United States Penitentiary, Lewisburg","institution_city":"Lewisburg","institution_state":"Pennsylvania","charges":"Federal destruction of government property — May 17, 1968 Catonsville draft-board burning of 378 draft files with homemade napalm","arrest_date":"1968-05-17","incarceration_date":"1970-04-21","release_date":"1972-12-20","sentence":"3.5 years federal prison","convicted":"Yes — federal jury verdict, U.S. District Court for the District of Maryland, October 10, 1968"},{"institution_name":"Pennsylvania Department of Corrections","institution_state":"Pennsylvania","charges":"Pennsylvania state burglary, conspiracy, criminal mischief — September 9, 1980 Plowshares 8 hammering of Mark 12A nuclear warhead nose cones at the GE Re-Entry Division in King of Prussia","arrest_date":"1980-09-09","incarceration_date":"1980-09-09","sentence":"3-10 years state prison; reduced to time served on appeal April 1990","convicted":"Yes — Pennsylvania state conviction, February 1981"}]}' || true

